segments.text: When he, he always put the game plan on paper, and we spent the entire week going over it.
And when the game plan came, I mean, I knew from the thing that he said, it's almost exactly what he wanted me to do.
I mean, we, Coach Spiler was almost the opposite.
I mean, he tried to, I mean,
He wanted to give you all the freedom in the world.
I wasn't used to that.
I liked it when Coach Martin would tell you what to do.
In certain situations, this is what you do.
I had no problem playing.
I was in better health.
Things were going better.
I just thought Coach Martin was about as good as he came.
Football in those days was so primitive compared to what he is now that there was no companion.
It was beginning to get a little bit more complex toward my junior senior year.
I guess I just didn't adapt as well.
Go through a typical week's workouts.
Well.
During the season.
Monday, Tuesday was the, Monday we generally would review what had happened the day, the week before.
And then, it was not a too much, too heavy a workout, and we began to practice in sort of a non-contact way what we were gonna do the next week.
And then on Tuesday, we generally, that was our hardest practice, and we would try to practice
as near under game conditions as we could, the things that we were going to do, and then we kind of eased up.
And Tuesday's practice would be about how long in duration?
Tuesday's practice sometimes would be until it got so dark that you couldn't see.
And Wednesdays and Thursdays were lighter, and Friday was just kind of a walkthrough.
That first year with Coach Norton, as soon as my afternoon classes were over, and I only had a couple, I'd break my neck to get down there, and we'd sit down and he'd talk to us.
Sometimes it would just be me, and sometimes it would be a couple of us, and sometimes it would be all of us.
And we would sit in his office and talk with him until the time to go to practice.
Describe his ethics.
I just have to say that I never saw or heard of anything he did that was questionable at all.
In fact, he told me one time we were sitting up
there by DeWare Fieldhouse.
And he said, this is toward the end of my, my leg was broken.
And that's why, I guess why I happened to be sitting there by him.
But he said, I made two mistakes at A&M.
He said, the first one was after the 1940 season.
He said, I had a chance to go to USC.
I said, I didn't take it.
He said, if I had to do over again, I would go to the USC.
So the second mistake I made was when the war was over, everybody that was on scholarship at A&M, when they came back, I didn't have a scholarship.
And that included guys like Luke Simmons that couldn't walk.
He said, if I had to do over again, I'd do it again.
You know, that's the kind of guy he was.
Did you get any impression of his feelings about the other Southwest Conference coaches at that time?
How did he feel about them?
No, I don't know.
I certainly didn't get any feeling of animosity.
I have the impression that they were friends.
Yeah, I think they were.
That they knew each other.
They had been in it for a long, you know, there was Dutch Meyer, TCU, and was it Rice?
Just Neely.
Just Neely and Rice.
Matty Bell.
Matty Bell at SMU.
And Bible.
And Bible at Austin.
And Kimbrough was at Baylor.
And Barnhill was at.
And those guys, they'd all been there for years.
And Coach Norton's private life was not questionable, was it?
Not that I know of.
All right, let's see.
Back to people that made an impression on you.
Were there any, you said Mr. Penberthy.
Describe him as the leader of the Department of Physical Education.
Well, of course, Mr. Penney was the one guy I know that I believe he, I honestly believe he knew every student in the school.
And he knew a lot about a lot of people.
The main part of the P.E.
department was the required P.E.
along with that intramural program.
Of course, the intramural program was pretty much under the physical education program at that time.
This was one place where everybody had a good time.
The P.E.
was recreation.
It wasn't so much, it wasn't drudgery at all.
Most of us were young enough, we still liked to play, and that's what D.E.
was all about.
Of course, a lot of it was competitive.
I mean, during the war, they started the mile and seven-tenths run, you know, and the swimming.
Most of us really enjoyed D.E.

professional PE department, for those of us that were PE majors, it was like, well, there was no school of education at A&M, you know, and the PE department, there were about three or four professors, and in the Department of Education, there were only three.
And who were those key people?
Well, let's see, Mr. Dowd,
Well, while you're thinking about it, this young guy who would later become a Southwest Conference football referee, Carl Landis.
That's who it was.
Oh, OK. Did you have any courses with Carl?
Yes.
Describe him as a teacher.
Dr. Landis was the most professional P.E.
teacher we had.
And he worked more at trying to get us as physical education majors to be academicians and professional.
He's the first, he's the only one in the P.E.
department who would have a paper to write would require you to footnote it and he was
Highly professional.
And I always appreciated him for that.
He probably had more influence on us as future professional people than anybody.
Was he already officiating?
Yes, he was officiating.
And he was pretty influential in getting a lot of us to start in officiating.
Oh, really?
Now did you do some officiating too?
I did until I started coaching and then, you know, officiating and coaching.
That's what I thought.
Can't hardly do that.
And did he have any impression on your brother to be?
Well, I don't know exactly how it really got started.
I know Barney Welch was probably, I know he was officiating by that time.
And they had a, and they may still have a,
a pretty active chapter of the Southwest Football Fishers Association here.
Dr. Landis was president of it.
So, Taylor Wilkins was another one.
He was president of the, that was active in the Fishers Association.
He's on the school board here.
Not Bob Nelson, but Bob Nelson's son.
What's his name?
Anyway, he was an old bailer boy, and he was active.
Let's see.
After the war, did you do much socializing as a student?
Well, yeah.
Of course, there was still, it was all men.
And most of the socializing was men kind of thing.
They'd drink beer.
Where?
Triangle.
Okay.
And there was a drive-in over here next to what's now the Ford place.
And if you weren't going to eat on campus, where would you go to eat a... Eat a hamburger?
Or a hamburger or a barbecue or whatever?
Well, let's see...
There were a couple of places at the north gate.
There was one place up above the Lipscomb Pharmacy.
And it went through several stages.
It was a pool hall and a beer joint.
a hamburger place, but our fare was generally hamburgers and chicken fried steak.
There were two, there were two or three restaurants in Bryan, the City Cafe and the Bryan Cafe, that we frequented, particularly, they sailed late.
And I remember Leon Hale,

wrote a column in the, I think it was, I guess it was in the Chronicle, since he's been in the Chronicle, might have been maybe with the Post, but about trying to find enchiladas like they made at the Pacific Cafe in Ryan.
Was there any place of shady reputation that anybody went to after the war?
Well, yeah, there were a couple of,
beer joints out here on the highway.
The Navels, there were two beers, right where 21 and 6 cross.
North End of town.
North End of town.
Where it's now Texas Avenue and Highway 21, where they cross.
Right where the Wieners is, there was a big beer joint and right across Texas 21 and that

was another one and one of them was navels and i don't know what i can't remember and then there was a there's a place out just across the river on 21 called the avalon and if you were going to drink hard liquor that's where you went because the liquor store was across the river all right now i met a man when i was in high school in orange because i'm a couple years younger than you
and he had once been over in one of those places when the Air Force Base was there, and his expertise was in gambling and so forth.
He was a dealer and all that.
Was there any of that out there near the air base?
I'm sure there was, but... Was there ever?
There were several.
The Avalon was a nightclub.
Okay.
And there were several other places out there.
I'm sure there...
that you could place a bed if you wanted to.
That wasn't much of my thing, so I'm not too familiar with it.
I can remember some of the guys talking about playing poker.
And Whiskey Bridge, straight out Highway 6, was that liquor store yet there?
Going the way to Snook?
Yeah, yeah.
It's just been leveled within the last two years.
Just the old building?
Yeah.
But it used to be on the, I mean, that was the new building.
There was one on the other side of the highway.
Oh, okay.
They were just a little frame.
Yeah.
But I guess they probably did pretty well financially.
Yeah, let's see.
MSC wasn't finished.
when you graduated, was it?
No.
Religious Census Week, was it?
It was.
Was it?
I think, I think my dad had a hand in starting it.
Okay.
And it was going on while you were a student?
Oh yeah, yeah.
And I can remember a couple of guys
I remember one of the men, I believe his name was Bill Peterson from Oklahoma City.
I think that was his name.
But this is, I believe, let's see, this must have been about 1948 or not.
It was during the time when President Gilchrist was having so much trouble with
and the Federals.
And my dad was looking for a speaker.
Were you familiar with the way religions speak?
You know, they would have a main speaker and then they would bring in representatives from all faiths and they'd meet in small groups.
But the main speaker was the one that my dad was always worried about, at least vocally.
At home, he would talk about, you know, who could he get?
I'm almost sure this guy named Bill Peterson.
He was the minister of the Christian church in the city.
And he had been a prize fighter, nightclub agency, and had all sorts of experiences.
And anyway,
My dad contacted him, and he explained to him the problems that were happening on the campus.
And he says, I don't know if anybody will attend these services or not.
And he says, I'll tell you what.
You get 100 people in the auditorium the first day I preach, and I guarantee you it'll be full.
Anyway, to make a long story short, he came down here and they had the, the first Sunday, I mean the first, on Monday they turned out 10 o'clock classes into 11 o'clock, you know.
And this was at Guyon?
This was at Guyon Hall.
And they had a pretty good crowd the first day.
The downstairs was mostly full.
a few people upstairs, and he preached.
And the next day, the next four services was standing room only.
I mean, he delivered.
And the first thing he said, the first, I remember the first, they had all the, they had all the ministers from the, on the stage, and they introduced him.
And he was a great big guy, you know, like 6'4", maybe weighed 2, 25, 35.
And the first thing he said, he asked Joe Boyd, the former All-American, the Reverend Joe Boyd, to stand up.
He says, I want to arm wrestle you right here.
They didn't do it, but that was the first thing he said.
And then the things that he said to him just appealed to the entire student body, I guess.
He was highly successful.
And they had two or three others that were, I mean, one man was the, was a Presbyterian.
And he was, what is he, at the Congress?
Oh, the chaplain for the- The chaplain for the Synagogue.
congressional chaplain at one time, and he was from California.
I thought I'd never forget his name either, but obviously my mind ain't going.
But anyway, he came in, he was a whole lot more serious, but he was, the religious emphasis weeks were really pretty successful.
Did you go?
Oh, absolutely.
I enjoyed it.
In fact, you know, there were so few places for people to
The MSE wasn't there, and the LaSalle Hotel was kind of going down the drain.
And my dad kept the minister, the primary speaker, at home.
Let's see, now there was a little Aggie, what was it called across from Sabisa?
Was it called the Aggie Land Inn?
Aggie Land Inn, yeah.
And it had about how many rooms?
Was there any other people?
motel of any sort in College Station?
Well, I think that's the blue top tourist court.
And it was strictly a tourist court.
It was at the East Gate.
So there weren't any night football games, so that the football, the visiting team, didn't spend the night here.
No.
They generally came on the train that morning.
Where did a basketball team go?
I don't know.
I've never thought about that.
So the other place to stay was at the La Salle Hotel, wasn't it?
Yeah.
I really don't know where they stayed.
I really don't.
I just never thought about that.
When you were a freshman before you go away to the war,
Where do you, where did you get a date?
Well, I was fortunate enough to have a girlfriend that, that whose folks lived here.
Oh, okay.
Okay.
Then when you come back?
When I came back, she was at Sophia Newcomb in New Orleans.
Okay.
And so I was in the same category with everybody else.
We just kind of, there weren't many girls, you know, but there,
The kid, when we were in high school, if a girl started dating an Aggie, then the high school kids wouldn't have an Aggie.

Yeah, she's too highfalutin for us, you know, and so when you, when we got out of high school, we got an A&M, well then the role was reversed if, you know, and we tried to, we tried to date the high school girls, and to a point, when we got out of
When we came back after the service, the girls from here that we knew were in college, Austin or Denton, for the most part.
And so we were just in the same boat with everybody else.
If you had a date on the weekend, you either had to go to Austin or Denton, or sometimes they'd come home.
We had a pretty good leg up on a lot of guys when these were on.
Now, were the Tesses coming down here on the train on those special weekends before the war?
I'm sure they were, yeah.
I know they, even after the war,
What I'm thinking about, when A&M would play SMU or TCU, they would come down here on the train the morning of the ball game.
And the reason I know that is that Dope Walker's dad was at Austin College when my dad was up there.
Oh, yes.
ULD Walker.
And he and my dad remained friends.
When I was a senior and I, no, when I was a freshman at A&M, when we had the football banter, my dad invited Dope to come down and go to the football banter with us.
Dope was the year behind us.
He was a senior at Holland Park.
And so he came down and spent the weekend at our house and went to the football banquet and two days after the football banquet is when I had to report to the Army.
But Bill went back to SMU and he went in the service and he went down to, he was at Brooks Army Base in San Antonio
And it was so far for him to go home on the weekends that several times he came over and spent the weekend with my folks while he was in the service.
And I was in the service.
I was gone.
And I never did.
I didn't know it, except my mother would write and tell me to go and spend the weekend with them.
Well, after the war, we played SMU three times.
One time, I was on crutches and didn't get to play.
And we played up here once and in Dallas once.
But when the train came down from Dallas with the SMU team on it, I went over and I wanted to speak to him.
Every time I saw that guy after the war, the first thing he wanted to know was how my mom was doing.
That's just how he had to be.
And I met him twice at the station here when the SMU team was coming in just to shake hands with him.
That's the impression everybody that I've ever talked to.
That's right.
That's the only impression I've ever heard of him.
The Missouri team, Missouri broke the 15-game undefeated streak up there.

And after the game is over, the Missouri quarterback, a superb guy named Buss Insminger, who is of the same quality of human being as Doak, he leads the whole Missouri team over to talk to Doak to tell him what a superb game he's played.
And they start talking, and pretty soon the SMU team goes to Matty Bell and tells him that the Missouri guys have asked them if they could stay and go to the
danced that night in Columbia.
And they said, coach, could the train just wait?
And so they did.
And I've shared that with a number of people to say, can you imagine today, after all of the cheap talk, two teams talking like that?
Then Doak's father got an honorary degree at Austin College while I was there.
I got to be one of the student marshals.
And here comes Doak Walker.
And no, no, no, they wouldn't accept special seats.
No, no, no, we're just like anybody else.
Just let us be seated.
And I thought, what a splendid, splendid family.
Let me stop there, and we'll renew this.
